Anonymous Tue 23 Nov 2021 07:24:20 No.43406906 Report

Reposting from a previous thread:
>>43317897

>was there something specific about my writing style that made it seem cheap and unwarranted?
Your writing style tends to prioritize characters and their unique perspectives. Much of the story concerns the human's personal lives, putting readers right into their shoes. Because of this, killing Roberta as an established character would only serve as shock value to readers. All the characterization you built up with her and Dominic would be greatly diminished as well. You have already demonstrated the Owl's willingness to kill through this murder attempt and her slaughter of woodland animals, so the point got across. It's only because there ended up being a witness present (Dominic) during the attempt on Roberta's life that the Owl relented, but this showcased an important boundary that the Owl didn't cross. If the Owl did actually kill Roberta, it would make it extremely difficult to empathize with her actions. In the wild animals rarely fight to the death over mates, instead opting for less lethal ways to demonstrate dominance. If the Owl were to kill in self-defense or due to provocation however, that could contribute to the story in a meaningful manner.

As for likeability, I think that it's part of the appeal of stories like these to challenge preconceived notions for an inhuman being. A language barrier, fear factor, or initial hostility would limit reader understanding. You got around these barriers by telling the story through the Owl's eyes, giving us a distinctly inhuman, yet still relatable viewpoint. This worked great because we now know that the Owl is capable of rational thought and fears yet still demonstrates her bestial side through impulsive and reckless acts. This desire for intimacy serves as motivation for her rash actions, something that could be understood if given enough time. It's that small inkling of hope that things could work out despite the odds which drive this unconventional love story.

Alien Intimacy (first half), Embrace by the Cold, and Distant New Admirer by Kaktus_nsfw.
